node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 03, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Photo by @francescolastrucci / Wild horses graze in the vast plateau of Campo Imperatore, situated in the wild Abruzzo region of Italy at an elevation between 1,500 and 1,900 meters (4,900 and 6,200 feet) and fringed by the highest peaks of the Apennine Mountains. Locally known as Little Tibet, the landscape can also resemble some of America’s West. Thanks to its natural beauty, the plateau has been the setting for many spaghetti Western movies and other international film productions. The area, a protected land included in a vast national park, offers many hiking trails from which one can experience sweeping views and spot wildlife. 
Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories around the world. #italy #abruzzo #landscapephotography #nature

node.text:
Photo by @mattborowick / Right after you pass the Beaver Meadows entrance to Rocky Mountain National Park in Estes Park, Colorado, you are immediately hit with an incredible view of beautiful wilderness. The highest peak on the left is Longs Peak. In the middle is McHenrys Peak and on the right is Taylor Peak. 
Please follow @mattborowick for more pictures like this. #colorado #mountains #nature #adventure #RMNP

I captured this image on April 9 while working on a story for National Geographic about the flower season in the Netherlands. For more photos and videos from different parts of the world, follow me @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic. #muhammedmuheisen #Flowers #Netherlands #Keukenhof

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / A walrus basks in the warmth of the spring sun in Svalbard. Female and male walruses both grow tusks, but they differ in size. Male tusks can reach up to 40 inches (102 centimeters) while female tusks are usually 25 percent shorter.
Walruses are classified as part of the Odobenidae family, Greek for “one that walks with teeth.” They have many uses for their tusks. They use them to help themselves out of the water onto the ice. They also use them to defend themselves from polar bears and killer whales, their main predators. They use their tusks to establish dominance in their peer group and maintain territory during mating season. They also use them to carve breathing holes in the ice and tear open bigger prey, such as seals, before eating them.
Follow me @DaisyGilardini for more images and stories behind the scenes. #walrus #polar #Svalbard #wildlifephotography #climatechange

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / Another objective of the Greenland Caves Project expedition was to reenter this cave known as Cairn Climb cave, which we had explored in 2015. Accessing the cave is quite difficult and requires climbing up a six-meter (20-foot) overhanging wall. Chris soloed the route first and then rigged a safety rope to make it easier for the rest of us to climb in.

node.text: Photo by @babaktafreshi / Being away from light pollution, like in this moment under the star-filled sky of New Zealand, is always a unique experience. You truly feel like you're on spaceship Earth traveling in the vast ocean of the universe. You feel connected to the past and future of this planet. It’s unfortunate this is not visible to most people. Join me @babaktafreshi to learn more. #twanight #stargazing #astronomy #nightsky #newzealand

node.text:
Photo by Brendan Hoffman @hoffmanbrendan / A border marker on a mountain ridge between the peaks of Talijanka and Popadija delineates the boundary between Montenegro and Albania in Prokletije National Park. Known as the Accursed Mountains, this remote Balkan range is beautiful and accessible, with these two peaks topping out at just over 2,000 meters (6,561 feet). 
Follow me @hoffmanbrendan for more stories from around the world. #montenegro #albania #prokletije #hiking #accursedmountains

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 01, 2021. May be an image of standing, outdoors, monument and castle.

node.text:
Photo by @francescolastrucci / Storied stone steps lead to the battlements of Castelo de Monsaraz and sweeping views of the walled city and surrounding Alentejo countryside. Suspended in time and perched on top of a hill overlooking the rural landscape, the village of Monsaraz, one of the oldest in Portugal, has been a fortified settlement since prehistoric times. 
Rural Alentejo, dotted with whitewashed villages, castles, and megalithic sites, is a vast land that runs from “the other side of the River Tejo” (giving Alentejo its name) to the Spanish border. It is a land of large estates with vineyards, olive groves, and cork woods where it is normal to have the pleasant feeling of being lost in time and space. 
Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories around the world. #alentejo #portugal #dailylife #history

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 01, 2021. May be an image of animal, nature and road.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / A lone camel crosses a remote, dusty road a few hours outside of Alice Springs. Australia has the world's largest population of camels because of their introduction in the 19th century from British India and Afghanistan. As technology advanced in transportation means, camels became discarded into the wild, where at one point the population peaked at an estimated one million.
